two small children. Even though her second marriage, to Auguste Dumont, made life more comfortable, the realities of her existence still prevented the fulfillment of her artistic longings. Ella Bird Dumont’s memoir is rich with details of the frontier era in Texas, when Indian depredations were still a danger for isolated settlers, where animals ranged close enough to provide dinner and a new pair of gloves, and where sheer existence depended on skill, luck, and the kindness of strangers. The vividness and poignancy of her life, coupled with the wealth of historical material in the editor’s exhaustive notes, make this Texas pioneer’s autobiography a very special book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBoley, Tommy J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCutrer, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78089740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292772144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292772144/original  a978-3-11-074535-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles